The research objective of this work was to devise a new approach for managing the power grid of the future equipped with ubiquitous power flow control capabilities.

The result from this project are multifold:

1) It has become clear that the traditional N-1 security concept does not fully reflect the security of the system; a formulation for risk was used and integrated into an Optimal Power Flow problem;

2) so called locational security impact factors were derived that provide an indication of the impact of a change in generation or load at a specific location on the overal level of risk in the system; these factors can be leveraged to make decisions on how generation and/or load should be adjusted to improve the overall risk/security in the system;

3) the formulation for risk was used to determine the optimal control settings of power flow control devices in order to minimize such risk; thereby it was taken into account that such control devices can react fast, hence, post-contingency actions were considered;

4) decomposition theory and iterative algorithms were used to make the solution of the problem tractable, i.e. the overall optimization problem was divided into subproblem which then could be solved in parallel; 

All of the above approaches were verified using simulation of different test systems. 

